Strategic Update 01.11.23 
 
@Nasdaq 100 Parties Like It's 1999: Traders Flock to Tech Titans and Send Index Soaring 7% in Four Days. 
 
The session on Wednesday seemed like a music video for Prince’s “1999”. 
 
Traders were partying from the opening bell, flocking into  
@Amazon $AMZN, @Alphabet $GOOGL, and @Microsoft
$MSFT, the internet winners from two decades ago.  
 
The@Nasdaq 100 index ended at 11,403, a gain of 1.8%. 
 
The advance was the 4th day, putting the benchmark #NDX us by nearly 7% since Friday.  
 
Most of this was predictable.  
 
Analysts spent the first week in 2023 downgrading all of the biggest technology names in the NDX, pushing their share prices to extremely oversold levels.  
 
Now traders are in scooping up the bargains, and causing misery for the learned crowd, and bears.

It’s all a bit strange that cyclical stocks are strongest even as the Fed tries to talk the economy into recession.

Morning Update  

We are going to start the session with a 230 point gain for the Dow and about 25 points for the S&P. The opening strength puts the $SPY at 287.20.   That's probably not the rally bulls need to get this thing back on track.  

Short term, the market is mired in a trading range. The top of the range is 293.50. The bottom of the range is 282. My guess is the index needs to break through the bottom of the range and test the 200 day moving average at 277. 

That's a lot of technical stuff but a real shakeout would be a good thing. 

I'm still expecting that the next really big move is higher as stock traders begin to realize that the trade war is over. Bond traders are in control now. They will not tolerate gamesmanship from politicos. Resolve the trade war, or the markets decline.  

The politicos would rather have a bad trade deal than weak markets. Bet on that. 

stocktwits.com/r/Risk_Rewarded

Morning Update  

Stocks were called about 200 Dow points higher overnight, then down 200 points about an hour ago. At this moment (I'm writing this just before 9:00 a.m.), it looks as though the Dow will open up 100 points.  

There is news. Some of the economic data points were stronger than expected. But don't lose sight of what is happening here. We are nearing an inflection point.   I continue to believe that the next really big move is up, not down.

Sadly, that move probably can't begin until there is a test of the 200 day moving average at 277 on the $SPY.  

The reason the next big move is likely up is simple. The factors that have been dogging this stock market are nearing completion. Bluster aside, the China trade war is over.  The Chinese want a resolution (on their terms) and President Trump needs a resolution to avert a major stock market decline.  

All of the news in the coming months will be about resolution, not escalation. 

stocktwits.com/r/Risk_Rewar...

@BadaBingCapital I don't believe it's inconsequential.  I think buybacks, in the case of these specific companies, is  planned strategy to manipulate investor sentiment. It's PR.

It's like Tim Cook claiming $AAPL is a services company. It's absurd. Service revenue is insignificant compared to iPhone. But Service revenue is growing fast, and iPhone, not so much.

He's telling the story that suits his purpose. Some investors buy in. 

It seems to me that ignoring the timing of share buyback notices misses the obvious intent. 

But we can agree to disagree. I'm cool with that. Like Fonzie:)

@BadaBingCapital I get what you're saying. My take is colored by execution and optics.

$QCOM had its merger with $NXPI blocked, and announced a share giant buyback
$AAPL reported extremely weak iPhone sales, and announced a giant buyback
$ORCL reported weak sales growth, and announced a giant buyback
$CSCO etc., the same

Managers, in these specific cases, are marrying disappointing execution with big buybacks. Regardless if buybacks are a good use of capital, investors (for now) are buying into the idea buybacks = higher share prices.

I remember when stock splits had the same impact. But I'm dating myself.

@BadaBingCapital $ORCL is spending 3x free cash flow on buybacks. Just my opinion, but it might because managers missed cloud and they have discovered a new way to push up the share price, beyond innovation.

But in the end, the market always discovers the truth.

If you have ever wondered why stocks like $ORCL, $CSCO and $AAPL are going up despite so-so fundamentals, there is an excellent story in the Wall Street Journal this morning.

wsj.com/articles/big-techs-...
$AAPL spent $75 billion on buybacks in the past year, accounting for about 4% of cumulative shares traded. $ORCL spent $36 billion, 3x free cash flow, according to the Journal.

Financial engineering is completely legal. It's also why declines have been spectacularly shallow. Bullish

Expect $SPOT bulls to return near 141.50

To be honest, if bears are going to mount any sort of move, they will have to do better than this. Trends in motion tend to stay in motion absent some competing force.

The G-20 conference is set for next week and that should keep the mood relatively buoyant going into a meeting with President Trump and President Xi. Expect selling to be shallow today. Bullish

I'm posting the hourly chart for clarity.  A break above the 291 level is going to be a breakout from a small bullish pennant. This will set up a rally to 295.

To be clear, the market is looking for the Federal Reserve to cut, or at least hint that it will cut short term interest rates soon, when it meets this week. 

Forget what bears are saying about a cut being bearish. It might well mean the economy is weaker than most investors believe. But it is bullish for stocks. And it is going to cause a lot of near term pain for bears.

That's the backdrop. Trade accordingly. Bullish

Yes, the stock may very well breakout today, but that is a more difficult trade. The easy trade, the one most option traders should look for, is the move toward major resistance/support. 

Leave the breakouts for more adventurous souls.

stocktwits.com/r/Risk_Rewarded

stocktwits.com/r/Risk_Rewar... Bullish

$LULU is going to open above the previous highs.

Breakouts above record highs on gaps are especially bullish. They represent the total defeat of sellers. It means the end of supply.

Everyone who bought the stock wrong, and wanted out, is going to exit at the open. They are going to be replaced with stronger hands, new buyers.

At least, that is the theory. If $LULU can hold above the 180 level today into the close, it will become an important new support level. A floor on stock prices. Bullish

$AMD, one of my favorite longs, rallied to the logical resistance point at 34 and stopped.

Risk Rewarded members sold the stock at that level.

Finding support and resistance levels should be the first order of business for any trader. Understanding where stocks should find buyers and sellers makes everything so much easier.

Traders should expect buyers of $AMD to step up again at 30.

stocktwits.com/r/Risk_Rewar...

The $SPY is called higher for a 7th consecutive session.

The key here is resistance in the 290 area. There is still no reason to be especially bearish. Shorting stocks/indexes because they have been strong is almost always an error.

Traders should short weak stocks/indexes.

I know, it seems simple, but it never feels like the right thing to do. We naturally want to buy losers and sell/short winners.

Wait for a setup before getting short the index. The $SPY chart may be near resistance. But it's definitely not bearish. At least not yet.

The $SPY is called higher.

What a difference a few days make. A week ago, bulls were in peril, the White House was talking the market lower even as the indexes tested the 200 day moving average, trade wars were developing on multiple fronts, and everyone was bearish.

Flash forward to today. Mergers are back, with a big $CRM deal, and a $RTX and $RTN merger, too. Analysts are bullish again. Despite the trade war, semiconductor maker $ADI got an upgrade this morning.

And the Fed, despite full employment, is talking about cutting short term interest rates, which is crazy.

Everything is falling into place for bulls. Or so it seems.

Traders should keep in mind that there is resistance in the 290 area. That level may be a near term magnet for bulls.

stocktwits.com/r/Risk_Rewar...

$APPL is testing the 200 day moving average 189 right now. 

The easy trade, the move back to resistance, is over. Traders should act accordingly.

The $SPY is called about flat on a weaker than expected jobs report.

Very often the early month deluge of economic data feels like reality TV. There is so much drama over almost nothing.

Keep in mind, the real driver for this market is the Fed. Every data point that suggests a rate cut is good, in a weird sort of way. I'm old enough to remember when the Fed would never consider cutting rates with full employment. But was a different era, I suppose.

The $SPY has resistance at 286.55. Look for actual sellers (not profit takers) to make a stand there. Ahead of that, there is no need to be especially bearish.

The Dude abides

Stocks are set to open higher this morning as bulls continue to push toward the next overhead resistance levels. That's cool.

Leading the push, possibly, is $AAPL. The iPhone maker is called higher following a new "buy" recommendation at Evercore ISI.

As a trader, my first inclination is always to fade bullish analyst calls. These events create liquidity, giving professional money managers an opportunity to dump stock. Many times, small investors get left holding the bag.

As I mentioned yesterday, $AAPL shares should rally to the 200 day moving average at 189.30.  Regardless what Evercore analysts think, it's likely to be tough sledding above that level.

My two cents.

cnbc.com/2019/06/06/calls-o... Bullish

$GME is called 30% lower.

If you're short from the break at $10, it's time to cover. In other words, if you got'em, smoke'em.

In a world of online gaming, over-the-air downloads and declining foot traffic, It's hard to wrap your head around the business model at $GME. It makes no sense.

Still, being short is hard work. There are so many ways to get hurt. Take this big win now.

Bulls had a big day Tuesday. The $SPY surged all the way back to resistance at 279.50. Today, markets are called higher and that means more pain for bears.

I'm not going to rationalize why the market is going up. It doesn't matter. It's going up. Bulls have bears on the run, for now, and they could reverse a lot of the recent damage in short order.

Some key stocks, like $AAPL, are probably headed back to test overhead resistance at the 200 day moving average. 

As an aside, the fact so many issues are trading below their longer term moving averages is bearish, not bullish. Perspective is important.

Stock picking is more important than ever. A few days ago I was scanning my notes and found hundreds of short candidates, and only a few longs; $GH, $ROKU and $MRK. 

Good trading is about doing the work, being humble, and more important, flexibility.

stocktwits.com/r/Risk_Rewar...

$AAPL reached its downside target at 170 yesterday and bounced, hard. 

In a world absent of tweets and China, $AAPL shares would clearly rebound to 189ish

It looks like a relief rally is in the offing for this morning for the $SPY.

Don't get too excited. The nature of bearish trends is violent, short lived rallies followed by days of despair.

I just spent the last two hours going through my notes and charts.

I understand the $SPY is near the 200 day. It never pays to get too bearish, but I found only 3 stocks that look bullish to my eyes $MRK, $ROKU and $GH

I found hundreds of terrible charts, broken stories and probable shorts.

Too often, traders look for stocks to buy into declines. Buy the dip. I get it, I do the same most of the time.

But this market is broken. I can't stress that enough. Lasting declines are  about narratives. Right now, politicians are taking dead aim at investors. That means valuation multiples will decrease.

Last week I commented that many momentum stocks were acting fine, despite the market weakness.  That is no longer true. $WDAY, $ZS and $TTD got taken to the woodshed despite excellent results.  

The price investors were willing to pay for growth declined. That's a big problem. Politicians believe they are in control. They believe the right comment at the right time will force investors back to the long side.

Politicians are naive. They may squeeze short sellers temporarily, but winning back investors will be much harder.

I hate it, because making money on the short side is much harder, but expect rallies to get sold until the narrative changes.

More coming.

Some will argue momentum stocks have no exposure to China. That's irrelevant. For the market to break, we need a change in narrative. Bulls have to give up. They need to sell winners.  

I will note that $GOOGL, $AMZN, $META and $NFLX have no exposure to China and they performed worst in the bloodbath last October.  

So, we're more bearish than bullish, obviously, but not all-in with bears, yet.  More coming ...
